"From
all
that
I
can
collect
by
your
manner
of
talking,
you
must
be
two
of
the
silliest
girls
in
the
country.
I
have
suspected
it
some
time,
but
I
am
now
convinced."
Catherine
was
disconcerted,
and
made
no
answer;
but
Lydia,
with
perfect
indifference,
continued
to
express
her
admiration
of
Captain
Carter,
and
her
hope
of
seeing
him
in
the
course
of
the
day,
as
he
was
going
the
next
morning
to
London.
"I
am
astonished,
my
dear,"
said
Mrs.
Bennet,
"that
you
should
be
so
ready
to
think
your
own
children
silly.
If
I
wished
to
think
slightingly
of
anybody's
children,
it
should
not
be
of
my
own,
however."
"If
my
children
are
silly,
I
must
hope
to
be
always
